    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN) would definitely be severely affected because it calculates distances directly between data points. If you plot age and income separately, a distance of 10 years is minuscule, while a small change of $1,000 in income is massive relative to age, causing points to appear very far apart along the income axis. Mathematically, in the Euclidean distance formula $\\sqrt{(x_1-y_1)^2 + (x_2-y_2)^2}$, the squared term for income will dominate the sum completely, rendering the age differences negligible in the final calculation. This forces the algorithm to ignore age almost entirely and base predictions solely on income values.",
