      "role": "user",
      "content": "got it. so basically the distance calculation is just broken if we don't normalize. what's the best way to handle this? should i use min-max scaling or standardization? and is one generally better than the other depending on the data distribution?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Both Min-Max scaling and Standardization work by rescaling your features, but Standardization (Z-score) is often preferred for datasets like yours because it handles outliers better. Since annual income ranges can contain extreme high values (potential outliers), Standardization will keep anomalies from stretching the feature space, whereas Min-Max would compress them to strict 0s or 1s, effectively hiding the outlier information. Additionally, Standardization is required for many models, like Linear Regression and Neural Networks, which rely on converging faster with features that have a mean of 0 and a standard deviation of 1. Ultimately, check your documentation: algorithms requiring output to be unbounded (like regression) usually need Standardization, while those strictly using bounded distance metrics (like KNN) can use Min-Max.",
